Plots

Box Plots

msleep %>% 
  drop_na(vore) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(vore, sleep_total, fill = vore))+
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.5,
               show.legend = FALSE)+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Total Sleep by Animal Type", 
       subtitle = "Carnivore, Herbivore, Insectivore, Omnivore", 
       caption = "Dataset provided by Tidyverse library.")

Box plots are particularly useful when working with descriptive statistical analysis, i.e. finding the mean and median values within a dataset as well as the interquartile range. This plot gives you a quick summary of how much sleep animals get based on their diet group.

Density Plots

msleep %>% 
  drop_na(vore) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sleep_total, fill = vore))+
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5,
               show.legend = FALSE)+
  facet_wrap(~vore)+
  labs(title = "Total Sleep by Animal Type", 
       subtitle = "Carnivore, Herbivore, Insectivore, Omnivore", 
       caption = "Dataset provided by Tidyverse library.")

Density plots are used to visualize a distribution of data over a period of time or in a given range. With this plot, again using the msleep dataset, we can see the sleep distribution of each diet group.

Ridgeline Plots
lincoln_weather %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = `Mean Temperature [F]`, y = `Month`, fill = after_stat(x))) +
  geom_density_ridges_gradient(scale = 3,
                               rel_min_height = 0.01,
                               alpha = 5) +
  scale_fill_viridis(name = "Temp. [F]", option = "C") +
  labs(title = "Temperatures in Lincoln, NE in 2016", 
       caption = "Dataset provided by Tidyverse library.") +
  theme(legend.position = "none", 
        panel.spacing = unit(0.1, "lines"),
        strip.text.x = element_text(size=8))
## Picking joint bandwidth of 3.37

A ridgeline plot is a collection of density plots that visualize multiple observations in a dataset like the one above.

Scatter Plots

penguins %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = flipper_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(sex ~ species) +
  labs(title = "Palmer Penguins: Body Mass vs. Flipper Length", 
       subtitle = "Sample of Three Penguin Species", 
       caption = "Data collected by Dr. Kristen Gorman (2007 - 2009)")
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

Scatter plots are used to analyze correlations among dependent and independent variables. In this visualization, I have separated and grouped the gender and species variables to better understand the difference between each categorical variables observations.

Lollipop Plots

chickwts %>% 
  group_by(feed) %>% 
  mutate(mean_by_feed = mean(weight)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(feed = fct_reorder(feed, mean_by_feed)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(feed, weight, 
             colour = feed, 
             show.legend = FALSE)) + 
  coord_flip() + geom_jitter(show.legend = FALSE, 
                             size = 4, 
                             alpha = 0.2, 
                             width = 0.05) + 
  stat_summary(fun=mean, geom = "point", 
               size = 8, 
               show.legend = FALSE) + 
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = mean(weight)), 
             colour = "gray70", 
             linewidth = 0.9) + 
  geom_segment(aes(x = feed, xend = feed, y = mean(weight), 
                   yend = mean_by_feed), 
               linewidth = 2, 
               show.legend = FALSE) + 
  labs(title = "Weight of Chickens by Feed Group", 
       x="Feed", 
       y="Weight",
       caption = "Dataset provided by Tidyverse library.") + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Lollipop plots are similar to bar plots and could be visualized in many different ways and used for all kinds of analysis. The above plot is one way, for example, to analyze averages. Each faded point in the plot are individual height observations of chickens; the lollipops represent the average height of chickens in each feed group, and the line down the middle is the average of all the chickens height observations.
